         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Colonial Botanist's Office ¶ William Street ¶ Brisbane ¶ April 29/92 ¶ Dear Mr Dyer...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">M92.04.29</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">Frederick Bailey to William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Letter press copy book 2, p. 18, Queensland Herbarium, Brisbane.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">To proof.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Colonial Botanist's Office</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">William Street</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Brisbane</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">April 29/92</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Mr Dyer</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I did not anticipate addressing you so soon again it being I think only Monday last that I wrote you re the Bellenden Ker plants — But this morning I received a note from Baron Mueller without explanation probably he thought it would explain itself.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">Note not found, nor a </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">letter to Thistleton- Dyer meeting this description.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> The epistle I refer to was a note which the Baron had sent to you [asking] for <name key="Trichomanes%20Sayeri">Trichomanes Sayeri</name> being figured in the Icones Plantarum saying also that when in Melbourne a short time ago that I could not find a specimen in his herbarium. From his note to you I should consider that he had no knowledge of the plant, and this is borne out by the references, for in Census he quotes [Brittens] Journ. of Bot. XXV, 163. (1887).<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">The species was described as </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-style: italic; ">Gymnogramma sayeri</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; "> in B87.14.01, p. 163; </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-style: italic; ">Trichomanes sayeri</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; "> was described under the joint authorship of M and Baker in Baker (1892), p. 15. M later listed it in B89.12.03 as </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">M </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">later listed it in B89.12.03, under </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-style: italic; ">Grammatis sayer</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">i (p. 234), and </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-style: italic; ">Tr</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-style: italic; ">ichomanes sayeri</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">  (p. 230), citing B87.14.01, p. 163 in each case.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I sent to England for this work but no such species is given in it — see my note p. 90 3rd {Suppl} to Syn. 21. Flora. The note you seem to have returned to the Baron and upon the blank [...] <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">aid</seg> that the fern in question would be or could be figured in an early part of the des. plantarum but you or Mr <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">Barker</seg>
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">In context, this must be </seg>
                        <seg style="color: #2221fe; font-weight: bold; ">Baker</seg>
                        <seg style="color: #2221fe; ">.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg> refer to another publication for the printed description. This will give you some idea of the difficulty I have to contend against in keeping the flora of this colony published up to date I dont know if such a rule exists, but if not you would be doing a good work by advising that in all instances like the present in which plants are described be distant botanists, that a copy of such descriptions be sent at the very earliest opportunity to the government botanist of the country or colony to which the plant belongs. This is a courtesy that might be expected, and if carried out would be a good help to botanists similarly placed to myself, and the avoidance of multiplying synonyms.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[...]<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">Rest of letter not about M.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
